div.p:
               It might further yet be tried, whether the growth of the various insecticidal plants, including Tobacco and Hemp, around and within vineyards would ward off the insect;

parties entrusted … ward off the insect is marked in the margin with a line.

                also whether the mere covering of the soil around the vines with the poisonous foliage of the Potato plant would keep the Phylloxera from penetrating to the roots of the healthy plants, and arrest the egress of the insect from the roots of affected vines; the effect of this procedure could be brought easily anywhere to a test. But the main-measure, to be relied on, should the Phylloxera have passed beyond exstirpation, would in our present state of experience likely be, to raise those American vines, the roots of which are left unattacked or not much impaired by this insect, and are fit to serve as stock for grafts of the European Vine.
